The paper deals with hyperspectral image super-resolution, which is a problem in computer vision and image processing. The proposed approach involves modeling the global spatial-and-spectral correlation and local smoothness properties over hyperspectral images using tensor nuclear norm, tensor folded-concave penalty functions, and 3D total variation. These techniques are commonly used in computer vision and image processing, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves optimization techniques, which are commonly used in machine learning and optimization, suggesting that the paper could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also involves image reconstruction, which is a common problem in information retrieval, suggesting that the paper could belong to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category. The paper could also belong to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category, as hyperspectral images are a type of multimedia data. Finally, the paper could belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category, as hyperspectral images are often used in remote sensing and environmental monitoring, which are areas that involve social and information networks.
